6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bybit calculates funding rates every 8 hours using time-weighted average price and interest rate components, providing stable but less frequent arbitrage opportunities. RabbitX updates funding rates hourly on Starknet, allowing for more responsive rate adjustments and frequent arbitrage windows. The 1-hour frequency on RabbitX creates more granular funding payments but requires active monitoring. Both exchanges use similar premium/discount calculations, but RabbitX's decentralized settlement may experience slight delays during network congestion."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"RabbitX's 1-hour funding intervals create more frequent arbitrage windows compared to Bybit's 8-hour cycles. However, Bybit's deeper liquidity pools provide more stable execution for larger positions."},{"question":"How do trading fees compare between Bybit and RabbitX?","answer":"RabbitX offers slightly lower taker fees at 0.05% vs Bybit's 0.055%, while both maintain 0.02% maker fees. RabbitX eliminates gas costs through its Starknet implementation."},{"question":"What are the settlement differences for funding payments?","answer":"Bybit processes funding payments through centralized clearing every 8 hours, while RabbitX settles on Starknet L2 every hour. Both methods are reliable, but centralized settlement typically has lower latency."},{"question":"Which platform is better for high-frequency funding arbitrage?","answer":"RabbitX's hourly funding cycles provide more opportunities for high-frequency strategies, but Bybit's superior liquidity and proven infrastructure make it more suitable for larger arbitrage positions."}]}]
